data.content:
Replace `[ExpectedException]` with `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>`, which lets you also inspect the exception:

```csharp
[TestMethod]
public void CreateUser_NullEmail_ThrowsException()
{
    var service = new UserService();

    var ex = Assert.ThrowsExactly<ArgumentNullException>(
        () => service.CreateUser(null, "John"));

    // Optionally verify the parameter name
    Assert.AreEqual("email", ex.ParamName);
}
```

**Why this is better:**
- `[ExpectedException]` can't tell *which* line threw — if the constructor threw `ArgumentNullException`, the test would still pass silently
- `Assert.ThrowsExactly<T>` scopes the check to the exact lambda
- You get the exception back to assert on its properties (message, param name, etc.)

Use `Assert.Throws<T>` instead if you want to match derived exception types too.
